<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundtable on Peace Proposals Held in Kabul </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD0303211394 Kabul Radio Afghanistan Network in Pashto 1530 
GMT 3 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0303211394 </F>
<F P=104>  Kabul Radio Afghanistan Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Pashto </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At the initiative of the special peace commission of 
the cabinet of the Islamic State of Afghanistan, a roundtable 
was convened this afternoon. According to a radio and 
television correspondent's report, the roundtable for discussion 
and exchange of views on different peace proposals began with 
the recitation of some Koranic verses by Mawlawi Seyyed Ahmad 
Hashemi, president of the Peace and Islamic Fraternity Council. 
An opening speech was then delivered by esteemed Seyyed 
Mohammed 'Ali Javid, minister of planning and president of the 
cabinet's peace commission. In addition to the personalities 
and representatives of various jihadi organizations, the 
roundtable participants included Lieutenant General Mir 
Anjamoddin, commander of air and air defense forces; and 
esteemed Abdol Fatah Nazir, president of the Servants of Peace 
Association. During the roundtable, different participants 
discussed various peace proposals and assessed suggested 
proposals. The following declaration was presented: 
  1. Islamic activities that are conducted by various peace 
groups are necessary and should be intensified. 
  2. It is necessary for suggested proposals to be realized in 
order to establish a unity of views and actions among peace 
groups. 
  3. It is necessary for a delegation to be elected from the 
society of the Islamic groups and for them to start work after a 
quorum is formed in order to implement and coordinate the 
suggested proposals. 
  4. It is necessary for the effectiveness of peace proposals 
that a joint association be established from representative 
delegations of various Islamic teams and for their work programs 
to be revived. 
  5. All social and jihadi forces of Afghanistan are asked to 
support good and sensible proposals. 

</TEXT>

